section.section:
The Department may deny an application for a compliance plan for an occupied affected property based on the following factors:
Failure to submit or timely submit a complete application;
Failure to submit or timely submit information requested by the Department;
The existence of prior violations by the transferee of the provisions of this subtitle or applicable regulations;
Prior extension of the compliance deadline under subsection (d) of this section for an affected property;
Potential or actual harm to the environment or to human health or safety; and
Any other factor the Department considers appropriate.

Subject to subsection (e) of this section, if an application for a compliance plan is approved, the transferee shall file with the Department an inspection report as proof that the risk reduction standard specified in § 6-815 of this subtitle has been satisfied, or an inspection report in accordance with § 6-804 of this subtitle, for each occupied affected property that has not satisfied the requirements of § 6-815, § 6-817, or § 6-819 of this subtitle within the following time frames:
Within 30 days after transfer of legal title for a transferee acquiring 1 occupied affected property;
Within 90 days after the transfer of legal title for a transferee acquiring 2 to 5 occupied affected properties;
Within 135 days after the transfer of legal title for a transferee acquiring 6 to 10 occupied affected properties; or
Within 180 days after the transfer of legal title for a transferee acquiring more than 10 occupied affected properties.
